{"id":"dumb","term":"Dumb","source":"Easton's Bible Dictionary (M.G. Easton, 1897)","html":"<p>From natural infirmity (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Exodus 4:11\">Ex. 4:11</a>); not knowing what to say (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Proverbs 31:8\">Prov. 31:8</a>); unwillingness to speak (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Psalms 39:9\">Ps. 39:9</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Leviticus 10:3\">Lev. 10:3</a>). Christ repeatedly restored the dumb (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Matthew 9:32\">Matt. 9:32</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Matthew 9:33\">33</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Luke 11:14\">Luke 11:14</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Matthew 12:22\">Matt. 12:22</a>) to the use of speech.</p>\n\u0000","refs":["Exodus 4:11","Proverbs 31:8","Psalms 39:9","Leviticus 10:3","Matthew 9:32","Matthew 9:33","Luke 11:14","Matthew 12:22"]}